Question 1 : What is Power BI and why is it used in businesses?
Ans :- 
Power BI is a business intelligence (BI) and data visualization tool developed by Microsoft that helps organizations turn raw data into meaningful insights through interactive reports 
and dashboards.
Power BI allows you to:
Connect to different data sources (Excel, SQL, cloud, APIs)
Clean and transform data
Create charts, dashboards, and reports
Share insights across teams
In simple terms:
Power BI = Tool to analyze data + visualize it + share insight
Power BI used in business :-
1. Better Decision Making
Businesses use Power BI to make data-driven decisions instead of guessing
Example: A company can track which product sells the most and focus on it
2. Real-Time Insights
Dashboards update automatically
Managers can see live performance (sales, revenue, operations)
3. Combine Data from Multiple Sources
Instead of checking different files, Power BI brings everything into one place
4. Easy Data Visualization
Converts complex data into:
Charts
Graphs
Maps
Makes it easier for non-technical users to understand
5. Performance Tracking (KPIs)
Track important metrics like:
Sales growth
Profit margins
Customer trends
6. Time-Saving Automation
Reduces manual reporting work
Reports can refresh automatically
7. Collaboration & Sharing
Teams can share dashboards online
Everyone sees the same updated data
Example (Business Use Case)
Imagine a food delivery company like Swiggy:
Track daily orders
Identify top cities
Monitor delivery time
Analyze customer behavior
All of this can be shown in one Power BI dashboard.

Question 2 : Name and explain the three main components of Power BI.
1. Power BI Desktop
What it is:
A Windows application used to create reports and dashboards.
What it does:
Connects to data sources (Excel, SQL, etc.)
Cleans and transforms data (using Power Query)
Builds data models and relationships
Creates visualizations (charts, graphs)
This is where you build your reports
2. Power BI Service (PowerBI.com)
What it is:
A cloud-based online platform.
What it does:
Publish reports created in Desktop
Create dashboards by combining visuals
Share reports with others
Schedule automatic data refresh
This is where you share and collaborate
3. Power BI Mobile
What it is:
A mobile app available on phones and tablets.
What it does:
View dashboards and reports on the go
Get real-time alerts and updates
Interact with reports anywhere
This is where you access reports anytime, anywhere
Desktop → Create reports
Service → Share & manage
Mobile → View on the go

Question 3 : Explain the Power BI workflow.

The **Power BI workflow** is the step-by-step process of turning raw data into useful insights and sharing them with others using Microsoft Power BI.

Power BI Workflow 

1.  Connect to Data

* Import data from sources like:

  * Excel
  * SQL databases
  * Web / APIs
* Power BI can combine multiple data sources into one model

2. Transform & Clean Data (Power Query)

* Remove errors, duplicates
* Rename columns, change data types
* Filter unnecessary data

3. Data Modeling

* Create relationships between tables (like joins in SQL)
* Define calculated columns and measures using **DAX (Data Analysis Expressions)**

4. Create Visualizations (Report Building)

* Design charts, graphs, and tables
* Add KPIs, slicers (filters), and drill-down features
* Organize visuals into a clean report layout

5. Publish to Power BI Service

* Upload your report to the cloud (PowerBI.com)
* Convert reports into dashboards

6. Share & Collaborate

* Share dashboards with team members
* Set permissions and access control
* Collaborate in real time

7.Refresh & Maintain

* Schedule automatic data refresh
* Update reports as new data comes in
*Connect → Clean → Model → Visualize → Publish → Share → Refresh**
Example:
For a sales dataset:
* Connect → Import Excel sales file
* Clean → Remove duplicate orders
* Model → Link customers & orders
* Visualize → Sales trend, top products
* Share → Send dashboard to manager

Question 4 : List any four data cleaning tasks that can be performed in Power Query.
In **Power Query** (inside Microsoft Power BI), you can perform many data cleaning tasks. Here are **four common ones**:
1. Remove Duplicates
* Eliminates repeated rows from your dataset
2. Change Data Types
* Convert columns into correct formats (Text, Number, Date, etc.)
3. Handle Missing Values
* Replace null/blank values with defaults (0, average, or text)
4. Trim & Clean Text
* Remove extra spaces, unwanted characters, or formatting issues
other useful tasks:
* Rename columns
* Split or merge columns
* Filter rows
* Remove errors
Power Query helps you **clean messy data → make it structured → ready for analysis**

Question 5 : Write step by step instructions to load the above dataset.
Here are step-by-step instructions to load a dataset into Power BI using Microsoft Power BI:
Steps to Load Dataset in Power BI
1. Open Power BI Desktop
* Launch **Power BI Desktop** on your system
2. Click on “Get Data”
* On the Home tab, click **Get Data**
* Choose your data source:

  * Excel
  * CSV
  * SQL Server
  * Web, etc.
3. Select the File
* Browse and select your dataset file (e.g., Excel or CSV)
* Click **Open**
4. Navigator Window
* A preview of your data will appear
* Select the sheet or table you want to load
5. Choose “Load” or “Transform Data”
* Click **Load** → Directly import data
  OR
* Click **Transform Data** → Open Power Query to clean data first
6. (Optional) Clean Data in Power Query
* Remove duplicates
* Change data types
* Handle missing values
* Rename columns

Then click **Close & Apply**
7. Data Loaded Successfully
* Your dataset will appear in:
**Data View** (table format)
**Report View** (for creating visuals)
**Get Data → Select File → Preview → Load / Transform → Ready to Use**
Example:

If you have a **Real Estate Excel file**:

* Click Get Data → Excel
* Select file → Choose sheet
* Transform (clean data) → Load
* Start creating dashboard

Question 6 : Define Data View, Report View, and Model View. Explain the purpose of each view.
In Microsoft Power BI, there are three main working views: Data View, Report View, and Model View. Each serves a different purpose in the data analysis process.
1. Data View
Definition:
Data View displays your data in a **table format (rows and columns).
Purpose:
* Inspect and understand your dataset
* Create **calculated columns**
* Check data types and values
* Identify issues like missing or incorrect data
2. Report View
Definition:
Report View is where you create visualizations and dashboards.
Purpose:
* Build charts, graphs, and tables
* Add KPIs, slicers, and filters
* Design the report layout
* Interact with data visually
3. Model View
Definition:
Model View shows the **relationships between different tables.
Purpose:
* Create and manage relationships (like joins in SQL)
* Build a proper data model
* Improve performance and accuracy
* Organize tables logically
Simple:
| View        | What it Shows | Main Use                    |
| ----------- | ------------- | --------------------------- |
| Data View   | Tables        | Check & analyze raw data    |
| Report View | Visuals       | Create dashboards & reports |
| Model View  | Relationships | Manage data structure       |
Easy Way to Remember:
Data View → “See the data”
Report View → “Show the data”
Model View → “Connect the data”

Question 7 : Discuss the different data sources that Power BI supports.

Microsoft Power BI supports a wide range of data sources, which is one of the reasons it’s so powerful in business analytics. 
You can connect to almost any type of data—whether it’s stored locally, in databases, or in the cloud.
1. File-Based Data Sources
These are the most common and beginner-friendly:
* Excel (.xlsx)
* CSV / Text files
* XML / JSON
* PDF
2. Database Sources
Power BI can directly connect to databases:
* SQL Server
* MySQL
* Oracle
* PostgreSQL
3. Cloud & Online Services
Connect to cloud platforms and SaaS tools:
* Microsoft Azure
* Google Analytics
* SharePoint
* Salesforce
4. Web & APIs
* Connect to web pages using URLs
* Use REST APIs to fetch live data
5. Power Platform & Microsoft Tools
* Power BI datasets
* Power Apps
* Power Automate
6. Other Sources
* OData feeds
* Hadoop / Big Data platforms
* R and Python scripts
Power BI supports:Files + Databases + Cloud + Web + Advanced sources**
Example:
A company like Real Estate might use:
* Excel → daily reports
* SQL → customer database
* API → live order tracking
All combined into one Power BI dashboard.

Question 8 : Split Owner Name to create two new columns as First Name and Last Name
Steps:
Go to Home → Transform Data (opens Power Query)
Select the Owner Name column
Click Split Column (from top menu)
Choose By Delimiter
Select Space as delimiter
Under “Split at”, choose Left-most delimiter
Click OK
This will create:
Column 1 → First Name
Column 2 → Last Name


